The '''Académie Suisse''' was an art school founded by Charles Suisse, and was located at the corner of the Quai des Orfévres and the Boulevard du Palais, in Paris. From [[Eugène Delacroix|Delacroix]] to [[Cézanne]], most major French artists frequented this place to meet colleagues or to study after the models supplied.
==Charles Suisse== According to Monneret, Charles Suisse was a former model of [[Jacques-Louis David]]. <ref>Probably not to be mixed up with the architect [[Charles Suisse]] (1846-1906), formed at the [[École des Beaux-Arts]], and since 1897 head of the ''[http://www.mediatheque-patrimoine.culture.gouv.fr/fr/biographies/suisse_charles.html Monuments historiques] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204054639/http://www.mediatheque-patrimoine.culture.gouv.fr/fr/biographies/suisse_charles.html |date=December 4, 2008 }}''.</ref>
==Students of the Académie Suisse==
{{div col|colwidth=30em}} *[[Paul Cézanne]] (1839–1906) *[[Honoré Daumier]] (1808–1879) *[[Carolus-Duran|Charles Auguste Émile Duran (Carolus-Duran)]] (1837–1917) *[[Achille Emperaire]] (1829–1898) *[[Armand Guillaumin]] (1841–1927) *[[Alfred Guillou]] (1844–1926) *[[Henry Lerolle]] (1848–1929) *[[Édouard Manet]] (1832–1883) *[[Claude Monet]] (1840–1926) *[[Francisco Oller]] (1833-1917) *[[Camille Pissarro]] (1830–1903) *[[Emile Schuffenecker]] (1851–1934) *[[Philippe Solari]] (1840–1906) {{div col end}}
