{{Infobox person | name = William J. Carpenter | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1827|04|17}} | birth_place = [[Braxton County, West Virginia]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1921|02|21|1827|04|17}} | death_place = [[Braxton County, West Virginia]] | death_cause = | resting_place = | signature = }}
'''William J. Carpenter''' (April 17, 1827 - February 21, 1921) was a legendary [[West Virginia]] [[outdoorsman]].<ref>John Davison Sutton: ''History of Braxton County and Central West Virginia'', McClain Printing Co., Parsons, W.Va., 1919, pp. 360-361.</ref><ref>Jim Comstock: ''The West Virginia Heritage Encyclopedia'', Richwood, W.Va., 1973-1976, Vol. 4, p. 826.</ref><ref>''Journal of the Braxton Historical Society'', Vol. 1, No. 1, 1973, cover photo and pp. 1, 2, 11.</ref><ref>William Eston Randolph Byrne: ''Tale of the Elk'', West Virginia Publishing Co., Charleston, W.Va., 1940.</ref> He was said to have had "no equal" in skills at hunting and fishing, and to be the best [[long rifle]] [[marksman]] in his community in his younger years—his skill in hitting difficult targets in [[squirrel]] hunting earned him the [[nickname]] "Squirrely Bill."
Carpenter was a descendant of Jeremiah Carpenter, the first white man to settle in the upper [[Elk River (West Virginia)|Elk River]] valley, at or near the mouth of [[Holly River State Park|Holly River]], in the year of 1784. His father was the first white child born in that section of [[Webster County, West Virginia]], created from [[Greenbrier County, West Virginia|Greenbrier County, Virginia]] in 1788.
Carpenter's extended family is known for producing noteworthy [[raconteur]]s and [[musician]]s.<ref>Gerald Milnes: "The Carpenter Legacy" in ''Play of a Fiddle, Traditional Music, Dance, and Folklore in West Virginia'', The University Press of Kentucky, Lexington, Ky., 1999, pp. 35-44.</ref>
